<BaseLayout title="Act Four" active="guide" description="Macbeth Act Four guide: the apparitions and equivocation, the slaughter of the Macduffs, and Malcolm's testing of Macduff, with scene summaries, analysis of form and structure, and verified quotations for the coursework.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">The Guide &middot; Act Four</p>
      <h1>Prophecy, slaughter, and what a king must be</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        Act Four asks the play&rsquo;s hardest questions. The witches tell Macbeth a truth
        shaped like a lie. In a castle in Fife a woman and her child are killed on stage. And in
        England, two good men have to work out what honesty, manhood and kingship are actually
        worth. The tyrant is at his most confident here, and the play at its most terrible.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What happens</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 1 (a dark cavern).</strong> The witches brew their charm and Macbeth
        comes to demand answers. Three apparitions rise: an armed head warns him to beware
        Macduff; a bloody child assures him that no man born of woman can harm him; a crowned
        child holding a tree tells him he will not be beaten until Birnam Wood moves to
        Dunsinane. Macbeth reads all three as guarantees of safety. Then he insists on one
        vision too many, and is shown a line of eight kings followed by Banquo, proof that his
        rival&rsquo;s blood will reign. Enraged, and learning that Macduff has fled to England,
        he decides to seize Macduff&rsquo;s castle and destroy his family.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 2 (Macduff&rsquo;s castle at Fife).</strong> Lady Macduff, bewildered and
        angry that her husband has left, talks with her quick-witted young son about fathers,
        traitors and honest men. A messenger warns her to flee; before she can, the murderers
        arrive. They kill the boy in front of her as he defends his father&rsquo;s name, and she
        runs from the stage pursued by her killers.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scene 3 (England, before the King&rsquo;s palace).</strong> Macduff urges
        Malcolm to fight for Scotland. Malcolm, wary of a trap, tests him by pretending to be
        greedy, lustful and lawless, a king who would be worse than Macbeth. Only when Macduff
        despairs, refusing to flatter such a man, does Malcolm reveal that he lied to prove
        Macduff&rsquo;s loyalty. News then arrives of the massacre at Fife. Macduff&rsquo;s grief
        is turned into resolve, and the two men leave to join the army that will march on the
        tyrant.
      </p>

      <h2>A closer look</h2>
      <h3>The apparitions and the art of equivocation</h3>
      <p>
        Everything the apparitions say is true, and every truth is a trap. This is
        equivocation, the practice of using words that mislead while remaining technically
        honest, and it was live and dangerous in 1606, when the Jesuit Henry Garnet was tried
        after the Gunpowder Plot and defended lying under oath as a matter of conscience. An
        audience fresh from that scandal would have recognised the witches as equivocators of
        hell. Told that &lsquo;none of woman born&rsquo; can harm him, Macbeth hears
        invincibility; the words are engineered to make him hear it, and to hide the man born by
        caesarean who will kill him. Told that he is safe until &lsquo;Great Birnam Wood to high
        Dunsinane Hill&rsquo; moves against him, he hears a natural impossibility rather than an
        army carrying branches. The apparitions do not deceive Macbeth so much as let him
        deceive himself, which is the crueller trick, and the resolve it produces is chillingly
        efficient: &lsquo;the very firstlings of my heart shall be&hellip; the firstlings of my hand&rsquo;, thought and murder now the same act.
      </p>
      <h3>The killing of the Macduffs, the play&rsquo;s cruellest scene</h3>
      <p>
        Shakespeare has kept his worst violence off stage until now: Duncan dies behind a door,
        Banquo in the dark. In Scene 2 the killing comes into the light, and it is the killing
        of a child. The choice is deliberate and pitiless. This murder gains Macbeth nothing;
        Macduff is already in England. It is tyranny purely as spite, striking a household that
        has done no wrong. The scene is built to make us love the victims in the minutes before
        they die: the boy&rsquo;s bright, teasing logic about traitors and honest men makes him a
        person, not a symbol, so that &lsquo;What, you egg?&rsquo;, the murderer&rsquo;s sneer
        as he stabs, lands as obscene. Lady Macduff&rsquo;s protest, &lsquo;Whither should I fly?
        I have done no harm&rsquo;, states the moral scandal of tyranny plainly: under a just
        king, innocence is a defence, and under this one it is nothing. If we ever doubted that
        Macbeth must fall, this scene removes the doubt.
      </p>
      <h3>Form and structure: testing, and the shape of the good king</h3>
      <p>
        The long English scene looks static beside the horror before it, and that contrast is
        the point of its placing. After a mother and child are butchered, Shakespeare slows the
        play right down to ask what the alternative to Macbeth actually is, and answers through
        structure rather than statement. Malcolm&rsquo;s testing of Macduff is built as a
        deliberate inversion: he lists the virtues a king should have by accusing himself of
        every opposing vice, so that the ideal of kingship is defined in negative, one quality
        at a time. When Macduff finally cries &lsquo;Bleed, bleed, poor country&rsquo;, choosing
        Scotland over the flattery that would save his own hopes, he passes the test, and the
        scene turns. The report of his family&rsquo;s murder then forces the play&rsquo;s central
        argument about manhood into the open. Told to take the news &lsquo;like a man&rsquo;,
        Macduff answers that he &lsquo;must also feel it as a man&rsquo;, insisting that grief
        and manliness are not opposites. It is a direct rebuke to the definition of masculinity
        Lady Macbeth used against her husband, and it repairs, in one exchange, the false idea
        of manhood that set the tragedy going.
      </p>

      <h2>Key quotations</h2>
      <table class="quote-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Quotation</th><th>Method</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;By the pricking of my thumbs, something wicked this way comes&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Rhyming couplet, foreshadowing</td>
            <td>The witch names Macbeth as &lsquo;wicked&rsquo;: to the supernatural, the king is now the monster. The chant marks how far he has fallen.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;none of woman born&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Equivocation, dramatic irony</td>
            <td>A truth built to be misread. Macbeth hears invincibility; the phrase hides Macduff, and the audience holds the trap he cannot see.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Great Birnam Wood to high Dunsinane Hill&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Equivocation, natural imagery</td>
            <td>An impossibility that becomes an army with branches. The prophecy comforts by describing a thing Macbeth cannot imagine happening.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;The very firstlings of my heart shall be&hellip; the firstlings of my hand&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 1)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor, parallelism</td>
            <td>Thought and murder collapse into one motion. Macbeth no longer deliberates; the man who agonised over Duncan now kills on impulse.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Whither should I fly? I have done no harm&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Rhetorical question</td>
            <td>The moral scandal of tyranny in one line: under a just king innocence protects, under this one it counts for nothing.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;What, you egg?&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 2)</td>
            <td class="m">Metaphor, brutal diction</td>
            <td>The murderer reduces a child to something unhatched as he kills him. The play&rsquo;s cruelty is made casual, which makes it worse.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;Bleed, bleed, poor country&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 3)</td>
            <td class="m">Apostrophe, repetition, personification</td>
            <td>Scotland imagined as a wounded body under the tyrant. Macduff&rsquo;s loyalty is to the nation, not his own advancement.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="q">&lsquo;But I must also feel it as a man&rsquo; (Act 4, Scene 3)</td>
            <td class="m">Antithesis, redefinition</td>
            <td>Macduff insists grief is part of manhood, rebuking the hard masculinity that drove Macbeth to murder in the first place.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <div class="box think">
        <h3>Think it through</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Are the witches deceiving Macbeth, or simply letting him deceive himself? Does the difference change how responsible he is for what follows?</li>
          <li>Why does Shakespeare finally bring the violence on stage in Scene 2, and choose a child as the victim? What would be lost if the murder were reported instead?</li>
          <li>Malcolm slanders himself for a whole scene to test Macduff. Is that clever kingship or a troubling readiness to lie? What does it suggest a king needs to be?</li>
          <li>Macduff refuses to separate manliness from feeling. How does his answer speak back to Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s taunts in Act One?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="box exam">
        <h3>Towards the coursework</h3>
        <p>
          Act Four is a gift to all three questions. For <strong>kingship</strong>, Scene 3 is
          the essay&rsquo;s clearest statement of the ideal: Malcolm defines the good king by
          naming every vice a bad one has, and Edward of England&rsquo;s healing touch stands
          against Macbeth&rsquo;s butchery. For the <strong>presentation of women</strong>, set
          Lady Macduff, a mother who protects and protests, against Lady Macbeth, and ask what
          the play values in each. For <strong>masculinity</strong>, Macduff&rsquo;s &lsquo;feel
          it as a man&rsquo; gives you the counter-argument the strongest essays need. <strong>
          Writing task:</strong> write one paragraph on equivocation in Scene 1, opening with the
          1606 context of the Gunpowder trials and looping back to show how the apparitions make
          Macbeth the author of his own downfall. Build the paragraph using the method on the
          <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>.
        </p>
